Part 1: Swagger Integration in Spring Boot — Without SwaggerConfig

This is the quickest, cleanest way to get Swagger running — with no custom config class, and disabled in production.

⸻

1. Add Swagger Dependency (pom.xml)

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springdoc</groupId>
    <artifactId>springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui</artifactId>
    <version>2.3.0</version>
</dependency>



⸻

2. Setup application.yml and application-prod.yml

application.yml (for dev/default profile):

spring:
  profiles:
    active: dev

application-prod.yml (to disable Swagger in prod):

springdoc:
  api-docs:
    enabled: false
  swagger-ui:
    enabled: false



⸻

3. Run and Access Swagger UI

Run in dev:

mvn spring-boot:run -Dspring-boot.run.profiles=dev

Access:
	•	Swagger UI: http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html
	•	OpenAPI Spec: http://localhost:8080/v3/api-docs

In prod:

-Dspring.profiles.active=prod

Swagger will be disabled entirely.

⸻

✅ Done! No SwaggerConfig needed, fully working.

⸻

Part 2: Validate Swagger Against Actual API Responses

You want to ensure:

“My Swagger documentation (request/response schema) matches what the API actually returns.”

⸻

Approach 1: Use Annotations to Bind Swagger to Real Models

Swagger/OpenAPI automatically uses:
	•	@RestController
	•	@RequestBody, @PathVariable, @RequestParam
	•	Model classes with @Schema annotations (optional)

Example:

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {

    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<User> getUser(@PathVariable String id) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(new User("123", "John Doe"));
    }

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(user);
    }
}

public class User {
    @Schema(description = "Unique identifier of the user", example = "123")
    private String id;

    @Schema(description = "Full name of the user", example = "John Doe")
    private String name;

    // getters and setters
}



⸻

Approach 2: Validate API Against Swagger Using Tools

Tool: Swagger Validator or Postman
	•	Export the OpenAPI JSON from /v3/api-docs
	•	Use a validator tool like:
	•	https://editor.swagger.io/
	•	Postman with schema validation
	•	CI tools like Swagger Codegen

They’ll compare your OpenAPI spec to example responses.

⸻

Approach 3: Integration Testing with Spring + OpenAPI Spec

Use libraries like:
	•	Spring REST Docs + Swagger2Markup (advanced)
	•	AssertJ + OpenAPI Generator to verify models

⸻

✅ Summary: Validate Swagger Responses

Method	What It Does	Effort
Use @Schema in model classes	Binds API docs to real model	Easy
Use Swagger Editor	Validates OpenAPI spec format	Easy
Use Postman or CI tool	Validates response format vs spec	Medium
Use Spring REST Docs	Generates docs from tests	Advanced but very accurate



